04390nam a22006615i 9780226488738DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264887387 a10.7208/97802264887382doi  a(DE-B1597)522651  a(OCoLC)1004848891  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF531b.L465 2018 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a152.42231 aLeys, Ruth, eauthor.14aThe Ascent of Affect :bGenealogy and Critique /cRuth Leys. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t[INTRODUCTION]. Setting the Stage -- t[CHAPTER ONE ]. Silvan S. Tomkins's Affect Theory -- t[CHAPTER TWO]. Paul Ekman's Neurocultural Theory of the Emotions -- t[CHAPTER THREE]. Richard S. Lazarus's Appraisal Theory I: Emotions as Intentional States -- t[CHAPTER FOUR]. Richard S. Lazarus's Appraisal Theory II: The Battle Is Joined -- t[CHAPTER FIVE]. A World without Pretense? Alan J. Fridlund's Behavioral Ecology View -- t[CHAPTER SIX]. The Debate Continues: Paradigm Change or Status Quo? -- t[CHAPTER SEVEN]. The Turn to Affect: A Critique -- t[EPILOGUE]. Where We Are Now -- tAcknowledgments -- t[APPENDIX 1]. Animal Signaling, the Smile, and the Handicap Principle -- t[APPENDIX 2]. Damasio's Somatic Marker Hypothesis (SMH) -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, emotions have become a major, vibrant topic of research not merely in the biological and psychological sciences but throughout a wide swath of the humanities and social sciences as well. Yet, surprisingly, there is still no consensus on their basic nature or workings.   Ruth Leys's brilliant, much anticipated history, therefore, is a story of controversy and disagreement. The Ascent of Affect focuses on the post-World War II period, when interest in emotions as an object of study began to revive. Leys analyzes the ongoing debate over how to understand emotions, paying particular attention to the continual conflict between camps that argue for the intentionality or meaning of emotions but have trouble explaining their presence in non-human animals and those that argue for the universality of emotions but struggle when the question turns to meaning. Addressing the work of key figures from across the spectrum, considering the potentially misleading appeal of neuroscience for those working in the humanities, and bringing her story fully up to date by taking in the latest debates, Leys presents here the most thorough analysis available of how we have tried to think about how we feel.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAffect (Psychology) 0aEmotions and cognition. 0aEmotionsxResearchxHistoryy20th century. 0aEmotionsxResearchxHistoryy21st century. 0aEmotions--Research--History--20th century. 0aIntentionality (Philosophy) 4aAlan J. Fridlund. 4aJohn McDowell. 4aPaul Ekman. 4aPaul Griffiths. 4aSilvan S. Tomkins. 4aaffect programs. 4abasic emotions. 4acognitivism. 4aintentionality. 4anon-cognitivism. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226488738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226488738.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles